<font color="#FF0000">ENGAGEMENT RULES/WWII WEAPONS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul  3  1:14:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
First to Joe,<br>
     I have no problem with the situation you described out on patrol in a free fire zone.  When you're in a base in the middle of an inhabied area that has three villages (one virtually a small town of several hundred people) within less than a half mile of your perimeter; there exists a need for some constraints and fire discipline.  Besides, the ubiquity of American troops notwithstanding, it was the South Vietnamese's country, not ours, and the often frustrating rules of engagement reflected their government's wishes more than anything else.  If our commanders found their troops could not operate under those conditions; we should have picked up sticks, and said to the South Vietnamese, &quot;Hey, the protection of inhabited areas is all yours.  Yeah, it was WAR, but the circumstances didn't allow us to as we damn well pleased.  And if we shoved our desires down the South Vietnamese's throats, how would we have been any better than the guys we were fighting?  Hobson's choice, ain't it?<br><br>
     I was there from July '68 to July '69, and watched the change; as the ratio of draftees to enlistees increased.  I believe the greater prevalence of drug use is an indicator. As I've posted elsewhere; the court martial load of drug cases in the Brigade went up into the 40-45% range of total cases.<br><br>
     One reason I personally have ambiguous feelings about &quot;our&quot; side is what I learned of how the National Police operated, at least in our area.  They made the greediest of corrupt cops and politicians in places like 1960s Chicago look like choir boys.  I would have rather they worked for the enemy for all the good &quot;?&quot; they did us.<br><br>
[Just a side note - &quot;professor&quot; is a nickname, not a title. Maybe someday after grad school, it'll be &quot;More of the Same&quot;<br>
and &quot;Piled Higher &amp; Deeper&quot;]<br><br>
To John Ratcliff,<br>
     In May 1968, while attending the MI aerial surveillance course at Ft. Holabird, Md., was given a tour of Edgewood Arsenal with a briefing on research into Soviet bloc small arms.  Various examples were shown.  There was a big push to develop something like the lightweight Soviet RPG to replace our heavy 90mm recoiless rifle.  Anyway, the AK-47 was covered, and we were told that the original versions; which were not fully automatic, were issued to Soviet troops in 1943.  How this relates to the info you have I don't know.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


